  <section>
    <h2>Types of Pet Allergies</h2>
    <p>
      Not all allergies are the same, and identifying the type is the first step toward effective treatment. The three main categories we see in dogs and cats are:
    </p>

    <h3>Environmental Allergies (Atopic Dermatitis)</h3>
    <p>
      The most common type. Your pet reacts to allergens in the environment — pollen, mold, dust mites, and grasses. In the Lake in the Hills area, seasonal allergens are a major trigger from spring through fall, though dust mite and mold allergies can cause year-round symptoms. Environmental allergies typically appear between ages 1-3 and tend to worsen over time without treatment.
    </p>

    <h3>Food Allergies</h3>
    <p>
      Food allergies develop when your pet's immune system reacts to a specific protein in their diet. Common culprits include beef, chicken, dairy, wheat, and egg. Unlike environmental allergies, food allergies cause <strong>year-round symptoms</strong> that don't fluctuate with the seasons. They can cause skin issues, GI symptoms, or both. True food allergies can only be diagnosed through an elimination diet — not blood tests.
    </p>

    <h3>Flea Allergy Dermatitis</h3>
    <p>
      Some pets are hypersensitive to flea saliva. Even a single flea bite can trigger intense itching, hair loss, and skin infections — especially around the tail base and hindquarters. Flea allergy dermatitis is treated by maintaining strict, year-round flea prevention and addressing any secondary skin infections.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Symptoms to Watch For</h2>
    <p>
      Allergies show up differently in pets than in people. While humans tend to sneeze, pets tend to itch. Bring your dog or cat in for an evaluation if you notice any of these signs:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Persistent scratching, biting, or rubbing</strong> — especially around the face, ears, belly, armpits, or paws</li>
      <li><strong>Recurring ear infections</strong> — one of the most common (and overlooked) signs of allergies in dogs</li>
      <li><strong>Hot spots</strong> — moist, red, painful patches of inflamed skin that appear suddenly</li>
      <li><strong>Excessive paw licking or chewing</strong> — look for rust-colored staining on light-colored fur</li>
      <li><strong>Hair loss or thinning coat</strong> — patchy or generalized</li>
      <li><strong>Red, irritated, or thickened skin</strong> — especially on the belly, inner thighs, or between toes</li>
      <li><strong>Chronic GI issues</strong> — vomiting, diarrhea, or soft stools (more common with food allergies)</li>
      <li><strong>Scooting or anal gland issues</strong> — sometimes allergy-related</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      If these symptoms keep coming back despite treatment, that's a strong signal that an underlying allergy is driving the problem.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Our Diagnostic Approach</h2>
    <p>
      We don't guess — we investigate. Effective allergy treatment starts with understanding exactly what's going on with your pet's skin and immune system. Our diagnostic process includes:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Thorough physical exam</strong> — evaluating the pattern, location, and severity of skin lesions, which tells us a lot about the likely cause</li>
      <li><strong>Skin scraping and cytology</strong> — checking for mites, bacteria, and yeast under the microscope. Secondary infections are extremely common with allergies and must be treated alongside the allergy itself.</li>
      <li><strong>Flea assessment</strong> — ruling out or confirming flea allergy dermatitis</li>
      <li><strong>Elimination diet trial</strong> — if food allergy is suspected, we'll guide you through a strict 8-12 week diet trial using a novel protein or hydrolyzed diet. This is the gold standard for food allergy diagnosis.</li>
      <li><strong>Allergy testing</strong> — for environmental allergies, we may recommend intradermal skin testing or serum allergy testing to identify specific triggers. This is especially useful if we're considering immunotherapy.</li>
      <li><strong>Bloodwork and additional <a href="/laboratory-diagnostics/">diagnostics</a></strong> — to rule out other conditions that mimic allergy symptoms, like thyroid disease or fungal infections</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Treatment Options</h2>
    <p>
      Once we've identified what's driving your pet's symptoms, we'll build a treatment plan that balances effectiveness, convenience, and your pet's comfort. Modern allergy medicine has come a long way — today's options are more targeted and have fewer side effects than ever.
    </p>

    <h3>Medications</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Apoquel (oclacitinib)</strong> — an oral medication that blocks itch and inflammation at the cellular level. Works fast — often within hours — with minimal side effects compared to steroids.</li>
      <li><strong>Cytopoint (lokivetmab)</strong> — an injectable antibody that targets and neutralizes the itch signal. One injection lasts 4-8 weeks. Well-tolerated with very few side effects. Great for dogs who are difficult to pill.</li>
      <li><strong>Antihistamines</strong> — helpful for mild cases, often used in combination with other treatments</li>
      <li><strong>Antibiotics and antifungals</strong> — to resolve secondary bacterial or yeast infections that develop alongside allergies</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Immunotherapy (Allergy Shots or Drops)</h3>
    <p>
      For pets with identified environmental allergens, immunotherapy gradually desensitizes the immune system to specific triggers. It's available as injections or sublingual drops administered at home. It's the only treatment that addresses the root cause rather than just managing symptoms. Most pets show improvement within 6-12 months.
    </p>

    <h3>Topical and Bathing Therapy</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Medicated shampoos and mousses</strong> — containing chlorhexidine, ketoconazole, or ceramides to treat infections and restore the skin barrier</li>
      <li><strong>Topical sprays and wipes</strong> — for targeted treatment of hot spots and localized irritation</li>
      <li><strong>Regular bathing schedules</strong> — to physically remove allergens from the coat and soothe inflamed skin</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Dietary Management</h3>
    <p>
      For food allergies, switching to a novel protein or hydrolyzed diet is the primary treatment. We also recommend omega-3 fatty acid supplementation for most allergic pets — it supports skin barrier function and has natural anti-inflammatory effects. Our <a href="/nutrition-counseling/">nutrition counseling</a> team can help you find the right diet for your pet's needs.
    </p>

    <h3>Environmental Management</h3>
    <p>
      Reducing allergen exposure helps every allergic pet, regardless of treatment plan:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Wiping paws after outdoor walks</li>
      <li>Washing bedding weekly in hot water</li>
      <li>Using HEPA air purifiers</li>
      <li>Keeping grass trimmed and avoiding peak pollen hours</li>
      <li>Year-round flea prevention — no exceptions</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

